The proof relies on the definitions of the spectral measure and the continuous functional calculus.
The measure $\nu = \text{toComplexMeasure}(\text{toResolutionOfIdentity}(a))_{x,y}$ is defined by $\nu(s) = \langle x, E(s) y \rangle$.
By definition of `toResolutionOfIdentity`, $\langle x, E(s) y \rangle = \int \mathbb{1}_s \, d\mu_{x,y}$, where $\mu_{x,y} = \text{cfc\_toComplexMeasure}(a)_{x,y}$.
Thus $\nu(s) = \mu_{x,y}(s)$ for all measurable sets $s$, so $\nu = \mu_{x,y}$.
By the Riesz representation theorem (used to define `cfc_toComplexMeasure`), $\int f \, d\mu_{x,y} = \langle x, f(a) y \rangle$ for continuous $f$.
Taking $f$ to be the inclusion map $\iota(z)=z$, we have $f(a) = a$ by the functional calculus.
Therefore $\int \iota \, d\nu = \int \iota \, d\mu_{x,y} = \langle x, a y \rangle$.

